---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import sharcCarlaDiagram from '../assets/sharc-carla.png';
import resultsTable from '../assets/table.png';

const withBase = (path) => {
	const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/?$/, '/');
	return `${base}${path.replace(/^\/+/, '')}`;
};


const projectLinks = [
	{ label: 'Paper', href: '#' },
	/*
	{ label: 'Code', href: '#' },
	{ label: 'Poster', href: '#' },
	{ label: 'Demo Video', href: '#' },
	*/
];

const highlights = [
	'Integrates the SHARC processor and control simulator with CARLA driving environments.',
	'Models perception, planning, and control latency instead of assuming instantaneous computation.',
	'Sets up safety-critical experiments where small delays measurably change driving outcomes.',
];

const scenarios = [
	{
		title: 'Intersection Right-Turn',
		description:
			'Comparison between high-frequency and low-frequency execution during a right turn through an intersection.',
		highVideo: withBase('/videos/Turning_250ps.mp4'),
		lowVideo: withBase('/videos/Turning_5ns.mp4'),
	},
	{
		title: 'Lead Vehicle Stop',
		description:
			'Front vehicle braking scenario showing how execution latency changes following and stopping behavior.',
		highVideo: withBase('/videos/LeadVehicle_250ps.mp4'),
		lowVideo: withBase('/videos/LeadVehicle_5ns.mp4'),
	},
	{
		title: 'Pedestrian Crossing',
		description:
			'Pedestrian crossing rollout highlighting how delayed computation affects reaction timing near the crosswalk.',
		highVideo: withBase('/videos/Pedestrian_250ps.mp4'),
		lowVideo: withBase('/videos/Pedestrian_5ns.mp4'),
	},
];

const roadmap = [
	'Connect SHARC timing outputs to CARLA perception-planning-control execution loops.',
	'Build repeatable driving scenarios with tunable processor and task-graph parameters.',
	'Quantify how computational delays shift metrics such as collision rate, comfort, and policy stability.',
];

const bibtex = String.raw`@misc{sharcdrive2026,
  title        = {SHARC-Drive: Hardware-Aware Driving Simulation with SHARC and CARLA},
  author       = {Anonymous},
  year         = {2026}
  }`;
---

<Layout
	title="SHARC-Drive | SHARC CARLA"
	description="SHARC-Drive integrates SHARC with CARLA to study how processor-level computation latency affects autonomous driving performance."
>
	<main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-10 sm:px-8">
		<section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl text-center">
			<h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-950 sm:text-5xl">
				SHARC-Drive
			</h1>
			<p class="mt-4 text-lg text-zinc-700">
				Hardware-aware driving simulation with SHARC and CARLA
			</p>
			<div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-3">
				{
					projectLinks.map((link) => (
						<a
							class="rounded-md border border-zinc-300 px-4 py-2 text-sm text-zinc-800 transition hover:bg-zinc-50"
							href={link.href}
						>
							{link.label}
						</a>
					))
				}
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="mx-auto mt-10 max-w-4xl">
			<div class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50">
				<video
					class="aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
					src={withBase('/videos/Turning_250ps.mp4')}
					autoplay
					muted
					loop
					controls
					playsinline
					preload="auto"
					aria-label="SHARC-CARLA teaser video"
				/>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section id="overview" class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-4xl">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">Abstract</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				In autonomous driving, control algorithms ranging from PID to nonlinear model predictive control (NMPC) must be executed
				within a strict sample period on embedded processors whose computational resources vary widely. The computation time
				depends on the microarchitecture, including clock speed, cache size, and pipeline depth, and interacts with the
				controller&apos;s algorithmic complexity in ways that are difficult to predict analytically. This work presents a co-simulation
				framework coupling SHARC (Simulator for Hardware Architecture and Real-time Control) with the CARLA driving simulator,
				enabling systematic evaluation of how hardware and controller design choices jointly affect closed-loop safety.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				<strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900">Index Terms</strong>:
				Hardware-software co-design, autonomous driving, model predictive
				control, computational delay, microarchitecture simulation.
			</p>
		</section>


		<section class="mx-auto mt-12 max-w-4xl">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">Overview</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				The main goal is to move beyond idealized driving simulation and evaluate autonomous policies under realistic compute
				constraints. Instead of assuming that perception, planning, and control complete instantly, SHARC-Drive makes execution
				delay part of the simulation.
			</p>
			<ul class="mt-5 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				{
					highlights.map((highlight) => (
						<li>{highlight}</li>
					))
				}
			</ul>
		</section>

		<section class="mx-auto mt-12 max-w-4xl">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">Method Overview</h2>
			<div class="mt-5 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50">
				<img src={sharcCarlaDiagram.src} alt="SHARC-CARLA system architecture diagram" class="w-full object-contain" />
			</div>
			<p class="mt-5 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				<strong>CARLA</strong> provides high-fidelity driving environments and sensor data, enabling simulation of various scenarios under
				deterministic, reproducible conditions. This makes it possible to evaluate autonomous behavior consistently across repeated runs
				while varying scenario setup, traffic, and environmental context.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				<strong>SHARC</strong> models multiple processor architectures to evaluate control execution performance across hardware. Rather than
				assuming perception, planning, and control complete instantly, it captures how processor-level timing and execution delay can vary
				depending on the underlying compute platform.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				By integrating both in a closed loop, we track control algorithm performance of the ego vehicle under hardware constraints. This
				lets us study not only what decision the controller makes, but whether that decision is produced in time to remain safe in
				latency-sensitive driving scenarios.
			</p>
			<ol class="mt-5 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				{
					roadmap.map((item) => (
						<li>{item}</li>
					))
				}
			</ol>
		</section>

		<section id="scenarios" class="mx-auto mt-12 max-w-4xl">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">Qualitative Comparisons</h2>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				Each scenario is shown at two latency extremes currently included in the dataset: a high-frequency execution setting and a
				low-frequency execution setting. This highlights how execution latency changes qualitative driving behavior across different
				traffic situations.
			</p>
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-3">
				{
					scenarios.map((scenario) => (
						<div>
							<div class="space-y-3">
								<div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50">
									<span class="absolute left-2 top-2 z-10 rounded bg-zinc-900/80 px-2 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-white">
										High Frequency
									</span>
									<video
										class="aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
										src={scenario.highVideo}
										autoplay
										muted
										loop
										controls
										playsinline
										preload="auto"
										aria-label={`${scenario.title} high-frequency rollout`}
									/>
								</div>
								<div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50">
									<span class="absolute left-2 top-2 z-10 rounded bg-zinc-900/80 px-2 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-white">
										Low Frequency
									</span>
									<video
										class="aspect-[16/9] w-full object-cover"
										src={scenario.lowVideo}
										autoplay
										muted
										loop
										controls
										playsinline
										preload="auto"
										aria-label={`${scenario.title} low-frequency rollout`}
									/>
								</div>
							</div>
							<h3 class="mt-3 text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-950">{scenario.title}</h3>
							<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-zinc-700">{scenario.description}</p>
						</div>
					))
				}
			</div>
		</section>

		<section id="results" class="mx-auto mt-12 max-w-4xl">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">Performance Results</h2>
			<div class="mt-5 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50">
				<img src={resultsTable.src} alt="Performance metrics across scenarios and processor settings" class="w-full object-contain" />
			</div>
			<p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				Metrics across driving scenarios and processor configurations. Miss rate <em>&rho;</em>: fraction of steps with
				<em>&tau;<sub>k</sub> &ge; T</em>.
			</p>
			<ul class="mt-5 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 leading-8 text-zinc-700">
				<li>
					Miss rate <em>&rho;</em> rises sharply as clock drops to 200 MHz in all scenarios (approximately 95-99%), along with
					large increases in average delay <em>&tau;&#772;</em>.
				</li>
				<li>
					Safety degrades most in lower-clock settings: collisions appear at 200 MHz for lead-vehicle stop (37) and
					pedestrian crossing (31), while the intersection turn remains collision-free in this summary.
				</li>
				<li>
					Tracking error worsens with lower clock in intersection turn (position 0.33 to 4.17 m, speed RMSE 5.9 to 11.3),
					and speed RMSE also increases for pedestrian crossing (11.6 to 13.6).
				</li>
			</ul>
		</section>

		<section id="details" class="mx-auto mt-12 max-w-4xl pb-8">
			<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-950">BibTeX</h2>
			<pre class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-zinc-300 bg-zinc-50 p-4 text-sm leading-7 text-zinc-700"><code>{bibtex}</code></pre>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
